page.title: 02BURNHAM OVERY HARBOUR - SSSI
page.content: Burnham Overy Harbour and the land, dunes and marshes, surrounding it will be incorporated into the Coastal area{ {Site of Special Scientific Interest}in 1986. It is already part of a{National {Nature Reserve}and of the coastal {Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty}and a{UNESCO Biosphere Reserve.} The area is already well known for the large flocks of Brent Geese (Branta bernicla), Pink-footed Geese (Anser brachyrhynchus) and White-fronted Geese (Anser albifrons) which overwinter here. In 1984 for the first time in recent years a ternery was formed on the dunes at Gun Hill, and this was reoccupied in 1985. The naterjack toad is also seen in the vicinity of Gun Hill, and there are various species of uncommon flora on the shingle and the marsh areas.
